The Importance of a First Impression: An Exploration of Chess¶

By: Rithik Sebastian¶

Motivation¶

Chess is without a doubt one of the most well known games, if not the most well known game in the world. The earliest recorded text about chess dates back to the 7th century. The modern version of chess that most people know emerged from Southern Europe in the late 15th century. What this means is that the current version of chess that we play has been around for over 500 years! Moreover, there are many new people who begin playing chess every day!

However, what's unfortunate for these new players is that there are over 600 million adults who play chess regularly (according to Chess.com). If there are so many people that have more experience than them, how are these new players supposed to get better? That's where the rating system comes in. No matter where you play chess, whether it be online or in person, you will use a rating system for any rated chess match. The most common of these rating systems is the ELO rating system, which is used by FIDE (World Chess Federation). What this system does is give every player a number, which is called their rating. When facing opponents that have a higher rating than you, you gain a lot of rating points by winning and lose little when you are beaten. The inverse occurs when facing opponents with a lower rating than you. What this does is slowly, but surely, shift your rating to a place that truly represents your skill level. What most chess websites and tournaments do is place players against other players with similar ratings.

While this system is great in that a new player will eventually get to place where they are comfortable in, starting off can be very intimidating. Since all new players are given an arbitrary starting rating (it differs by the system), it's very possible that a new player will have to play against players who are much more skilled than they are and be discouraged from playing the game.

What I want to do through this Data Science tutorial is help give these new players a leg up in their first couple of matches. To do this, I am going to explore just how important the first move of the match is. Any chess player will tell you that learning certain openings to a game will help you fare better, but for players who are brand new to the game, it will be hard for them to grasp how to do these openings (especially since each opening has variants based on your opponents' moves). As such, finding out how well the first move of the match affects the outcome of a game through this tutorial then simply reacting to your opponent's moves will be the best strategy for these beginners.

Setting Up¶

Before we can even start doing any work with our data, we must first do a setup. Specifically, we will be importing a few libraries that will our analysis. These libraries are:

  • pandas, a library that uses a type of table called DataFrames which will be useful in our analysis
  • numpy, a library that will be useful for mathematical calculations
  • re, a library that will be used for regular expressions
  • matplotlib, a library that will be used for plotting
  • sklearn, a library that will be used for regression analysis
  • scipy, another library that will be used for regression analysis

Data Collection¶

Now that we've added all of our libraries, we now need to get all of our data. The dataset that we will be using for this tutorial will consist of multiple chess matches over the span of a month. I obtained this dataset from the online chess website lichess.org through another website, Kaggle, where the data was put into a format that I could use here. Lichess is one of most popular chess websites in the world. In addition to this, Lichess publishes all of the data from every chess match that is played on their website on a monthly basis. This serves us greatly because it gives real data about how players play at different rankings. For this exploration, we will be using the chess data from August 2014. This is purely due to the fact that the data for more recent months takes up too much space for us to be able to do this exploration quickly and effectively.

In [5]:
# Given the list of moves in chess notation, this function will compute the first move and return that value
def move1(movelist):
    move = re.search('^1\. (N?[a-h][34])', movelist)
    if move:
        return move.group(1)
    else:
        # returns NaN if there's an problem in the data
        return np.NaN
In [6]:
# Given the result of the match, this function returns the number of points (0 for a loss, 0.5 for a tie, 1 for a win)
def result_to_num(result):
    if (result == "Black Wins"):
        return 0
    elif (result == "White Wins"):
        return 1
    elif (result == "Draw"):
        return 0.5
    else:
        # Returns NaN if given an unexpected value
        return np.NaN
In [7]:
# Creates new columns using the recently defined function
chess_data["Move 1"] = chess_data["PGN"].map(lambda moves: move1(moves))
chess_data["Result Points"] = chess_data["Result"].map(lambda res: result_to_num(res))
chess_data["White Rating"] = chess_data["Average Rating"] + chess_data["Rating Difference"]/2

# Removes any rows where the match was a correspondence game
chess_data = chess_data[chess_data["Mode"] != "Correspondence"].reset_index().drop(columns = "index")

What we've done in the above code chunks is four different modifications to our dataset. Firstly, since we need to use the first move of the match in our analysis, we will use a regular expression to extract the first move of each match from the "PGN" column, which contains the entirety of each game in chess notation. Next, we will convert the Rating column, which currently contains categorical data, into more usable numerical data. This is done by giving a white win a value of 1, a black win a value of 0, and a draw a value of 0.5. Third, since our focus in this tutorial is the white player, the rating of the white player is more useful than the average. Luckily, we can use the average rating and the rating difference columns to determine the rating of the white player. Lastly, we want to remove any rows in our DataFrame where the game mode is correspondence. This is because, according to Lichess's rules, players in correspondence games (and only correspondence games) are allowed to use any resources to help with their opening. As such, including correspondence games would skew our results.

Now that we've modified our data to our liking, we can drop the old columns that we'll no longer need.

Exploratory Analysis/Visualization¶

Now that we have a table we're comfortable with, let's start to do some visualization and analysis. First, let's look at what the competition looks like for our new player. To do that, we'll make a scatter plot to visualize the Rating Difference between players at different ratings for white.

There are a lot of points to use, so we can observe a pretty clear trend in this data. It seems as though when the rating of the white player increases, the difference in rating for matches increases at a linear rate. This makes sense intuitively since there are only so many high ranked players for other high ranked players to play against. Since this plot seems to be linear, let's attempt to place a linear regression onto it.

Hypothesis Testing¶

For this section, we are going to use some hypothesis testing to see how important the first move of a chess match is. But before this, we want to see if white's rating also has an impact.

This is interesting because we can that where before, the graph of White Rating vs. Result Points seemed akin a tangent curve, these graphs seem almost linear. Here is where we can do our hypothesis test.

To see if these relationships are linear, we will make our null hypothesis for each move that there is no linear relationship between white's rating and the average result points and our alternative hypothesis that there is some linear relationship between white's rating and the average result points. Another way of saying this is that the null hypothesis is that the slope of a regression line between white's rating and the average result points is 0 and our alternative hypothesis is that the slope of a regression line between white's rating and the average result points is not 0.

As such, we can perform our hypothesis test by constructing linear regressions for each first move and observing the p-value (the probability that the slope is what we find assuming that the null hypothesis holds true). If the p-value is lower than our significance level (which I have chosen to be 0.01), we can reject our null hypothesis.

In [22]:
# Prints p value and slope for each first move
print("move\tp value\t\t\tslope")
for move in first_moves:
    curr = chess_data[chess_data["Move 1"] == move].groupby("White Rating").mean().reset_index()
    lm2 = stats.linregress(curr["White Rating"],curr["Result Points"])
    print(move + ":\t" + str(lm2.pvalue) + "\t" + str(lm2.slope))

As we can see from the output above, all of our p values are less than our significance level of 0.01. As such, we can reject the null hypothesis for each first move and say that there is some linear relationship between white's rating and result points. What we can also observe is that the value of the slope for each first move is, in fact, different from each other. While this difference may seem small, we must remember that ratings have rather high values, so the small differences between each slope are magnified as such high magnitudes.

Now seeing that the first move will have an impact on the result points, we will use sklearn's linear regression one last time to determine the best first move for our new player. Before we can make the regression, we will have to add some columns to our table. Since the "Move 1" column contains categorical data, we need to convert it to numerical data in our to incorporate it into our linear regression. To do this, we will create columns for each first move that contain a 1 if a match started with that move or a 0 if it didn't. Since we've determined that there is also a different effect when considering both white's rating and the first move, we will also add interaction columns between white's rating and the first moves.

Our regression is complete! From the output above, we can see the coefficients for each of the columns that were used to make the regression. # Given a white rating, a rating difference, and a first move, this function returns an array to feed as
# the prediction for our regression
def predict_format(rating, diff, move):
    if (move in first_moves):
        res = np.zeros(40)
        res[0] = rating
        if (move != "Na3"):
            index = first_moves.tolist().index(move)
            res[index+1] = 1
            res[index+20] = rating
        return [res]
    else:
        return []

# Creating a final DataFrame which shows the odds of winning for each first move for our new chess player
move_df = pd.DataFrame()
move_df["Move 1"] = first_moves
move_df["Prediction"] = move_df["Move 1"].map(lambda move: lm_wmove1.predict(predict_format(1500, start_difference, move))[0])
move_df.sort_values(by = "Prediction")

Conclusion¶

With this last DataFrame, we can observe that the first move that maximizes our new chess player's chance of winning is b4, while the first move that minimizes our new chess player's chance of winning is Nh3. With a little more external research, we can see why these results make sense. b4 is the opening move of the Sokolsky Opening, which is an uncommon opening and likely an opening that our player's opponent might not be accustomed to. At the same time, Nh3 is a rather bad move as it puts our player's knight (that's what the N stands for) in a rather poor location.

With that, we have completed this tutorial. We have completed the steps of the Data Science Pipeline by

  1. Collecting our data
  2. Refining it to meet our needs
  3. Doing initial visualization and analysis
  4. Applying a Hypothesis Test to check for relationships, and
  5. Drew a useful conclusion from our results
